I'm an American, and I taught myself to speak Japanese.<br>
<br>
I have some advice for your American friend.<br>
<br>
1) Start with ROMAJI.  Use silly jokes and word-associations to remember Japanese words.<br>
For example, &quot;naze&quot; (why) sounds like &quot;nazi&quot; (german soldiers).  Using Romaji makes the words more memorable, and less foreign.<br>
<br>
2) Pay close attention to the ACCENTS (stresses within the words).  Japanese is famous as a language that sounds like a monotone, but the stresses of words are actually very important.  A good dictionary should have those accents, DEFINITELY.<br>
<br>
3) I strongly recommend &quot;Collins-Shubun English-Japanese dictionary&quot;, ISBN 0-00-433405-1<br>
(1500 yen, $12 US).<br>
BUY THIS, BUY THIS, BUY THIS.<br>
It's the first, last, and best dictionary for him.<br>
It has alot of sample sentences, and all sentences are in BOTH Romaji and Hiragana/katakana/Kanji.<br>
(Don't get the smaller &quot;gem&quot; version... it's only a little smaller, but the vocabulary is distinctly smaller, and the small lettering will make his eyes suffer.<br>
<br>
4) Tell him, &quot;Concentrate on the -masu forms of verbs, and memorize THOSE, not the -RU forms of the verbs, which are great for dictionaries and horrible for conversation.<br>
<br>
5) A good (short, clear) grammar book is &quot;Essential Japanese Grammar&quot; by Everett F. Bleiler, ISBN 0-486-21027-8   (600 yen / $4.50 US).<br>
<br>
6) If you have a little money left, buy &quot;Martin's Pocket Dictionary&quot; from Tuttle Language Library (ISBN 0-8048-1588-7 ). It's a weak English-Japanese/Japanese-English dictionary, in Romaji only.  It's pocket-size, silver cover.It's worth having ONLY because it has the -masu forms of verbs in the Japanese-to-English section of the book.<br>
---------------<br>
